The name "Reisai" began to be used in [[Early modern period|the early modern period]] ; before that, the festival was called {{ill|10=ja|11=大祭|Omatsuri|12=draft|12=draft}} (Grand Festival) or Onmatsuri (Imperial Festival), or the shrine's name was added to the word "matsuri" (festival), resulting in names such as Kasuga Festival or Iwashimizu Festival. Even today, this name is recorded in the "Shoreki" section of the {{ill|Jingū calendar|ja|神宮暦|12=draft|12=draft}}. In the early modern period, illustrated {{ill|Meisho zue|fr|lt=guides to famous places|12=draft|12=draft}} around the country would often include entries such as "XX Shrine Annual Festival on XX Month XX Day," which shows that it had become common to refer to important festivals that represent a shrine as annual festivals.<ref name=":0" />

Under the Meiji shrine system, annual festivals, along with [[Kinensai|the Niiname-sai]] and [[Niiname-no-Matsuri|Kinen-sai festivals]], were designated as 'great festivals', and [[Chokusaisha|imperial envoys]] offering {{ill|10=ja|11=幣帛|sacred offerings|12=draft|12=draft}} were sent to national and prefectural shrines, local shrines, village shrines, and some village shrines (shrines designated for the offering of sacred offerings) to make offerings from the state and the imperial family.<ref name=":0" />

After the Second World War, the system of offerings of sacred offerings from the government was abolished, but [[Chokusaisha|imperial envoys]] still visit imperial shrines during annual festivals. At other shrines, instead of the official system of offering heihaku, the Association of Shinto Shrines offers 'Honchohei' (offerings from the Association of Shinto Shrines) (however, this is limited to shrines that are under the jurisdiction of the [[Association of Shinto Shrines]] ).

